The number of rational points of hyperelliptic curves over subsets of finite fields

Kristina Nelson Department of Mathematics, University of California, Berkeley, CA 94720-3840 krisn@math.berkeley.edu ,  József Solymosi Department of Mathematics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada V6T 1Z2 solymosi@math.ubc.ca ,  Foster Tom Department of Mathematics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada V6T 1Z2 foster@math.ubc.ca  and  Ching Wong Department of Mathematics, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada V6T 1Z2 ching@math.ubc.ca
Abstract.

We prove two related concentration inequalities concerning the number of rational points of hyperelliptic curves over subsets of a finite field. In particular, we investigate the probability of a large discrepancy between the numbers of quadratic residues and non-residues in the image of such subsets over uniformly random hyperelliptic curves of given degrees. We find a constant probability of such a high difference and show the existence of sets with an exceptionally large discrepancy.

1. Introduction

Let q𝑞q be a prime power and let 𝔽qsubscript𝔽𝑞\mathbb{F}_{q} be the finite field with q𝑞q elements. Suppose that q𝑞q is odd. With probability about 1/2121/2 there is no point in E​(𝔽q)𝐸subscript𝔽𝑞E(\mathbb{F}_{q}) having the first coordinate x∈𝔽q𝑥subscript𝔽𝑞x\in\mathbb{F}_{q}. Therefore, #​E​(𝔽q)#𝐸subscript𝔽𝑞\#E(\mathbb{F}_{q}) is expected to be close to q+1𝑞1q+1. Indeed, Hasse [2] proved, in 1936, that the error in this estimate is at most 2​q2𝑞2\sqrt{q}:

|#​E​(𝔽q)−(q+1)|≤2​q.#𝐸subscript𝔽𝑞𝑞12𝑞|\#E(\mathbb{F}_{q})-(q+1)|\leq 2\sqrt{q}.

Knowledge of #​E​(𝔽q)#𝐸subscript𝔽𝑞\#E(\mathbb{F}_{q}) is crucial in elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which is considered to be more efficient than the classical cryptosystems, like RSA [6]. The security of ECC depends on the difficulty of solving the Elliptic Curve Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP). The best known algorithm to solve ECDLP in finite fields is Pollard’s Rho Algorithm [5], which requires O​(p)𝑂𝑝O(\sqrt{p}) time complexity, where p𝑝p is the prime factor of q𝑞q. However, some well studied elliptic curves or elliptic curves of certain forms are not good candidates for ECC. For instance, if the number of rational points of an elliptic curve E𝐸E in 𝔽psubscript𝔽𝑝\mathbb{F}_{p} is exactly p𝑝p, where p𝑝p is a prime, then the running time of solving the ECDLP is O​(log⁡p)𝑂𝑝O(\log{p}), see [9]. Using verifiably random elliptic curves in ECC can ensure higher security. Hyperelliptic curves can also be used in cryptography, see [1] for more details; however, the verifiability of random hyperelliptic curves is much harder, see [3, 7].

In this paper, we investigate the behaviour of random hyperelliptic curves over subsets S𝑆S of 𝔽qsubscript𝔽𝑞\mathbb{F}_{q}. 3. Proofs of the Theorems
